TLDR;

  • With increased PO2, Haldane effect causes hypercapnia.
  • Increased PaO2 opens up pulmonary capillaries causing increased perfusion of underventilated alveoli -> increased V/Q mismatch

Interstitial lung disease

[!INFO] Diffuse parenchymal lung diseases = Interstitial lung diseases
Source

Classification

Pathogenesis

Obviously, pathogenesis is somewhat different between the varying causes.
But overall, the changes are probably confined to the interstitial regions (i.e between the alveoli) as shown below.

[!INFO]

This schematic view of depicts the main differences in cellular composition in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF) and systemic sclerosis-associated interstitial lung disease (SSc-ILD) compared with normal physiological cellular components. Th2: T-helper cell type 2; AEC: alveolar epithelial cell.

Clinical features

Source
The purpose of looking for clinical signs is to

  1. diagnose ILD
  2. Look for a possible associated disease (left most box in the classification above)
  • Patients may have a history of occupational exposure
  • Pulmonary findings:
    • Progressive exertional breathlessness (dyspnea) and a nonproductive cough are the commonest symptoms.
    • Symptoms in addition to this may (haemoptysis, wheeze, pleural effusion) may suggest a specific diagnosis.
    • Examination: Crackles / crepitations in the bases(but less likely to be heard in granulomatous diseases like sarcoidosis)
  • Extrapulmonary findings
    • May also point to a particular cause.
    • Clubbing is one example but is a late feature: See table below
  • Restrictive pattern on spirometry

Interstitial lung diseases and clubbingi

Clubbing (+) Clubbing (-)
IPF Sarcoidosis
Asbestosis Hypersensitivity pneumonitis
Pulmonary Langerhans cell histiocytosis

Other disorders associated with clubbing include cystic fibrosis, pulmonary arteriovenous malformations, cyanotic heart disease, malignancies of the lung and pleura, and inflammatory bowel diseas

Radiological features

  • Radiological features of ILD are not diagnostic for the underlying aetiology Source
    ~~- Generally, ILD's cause infiltrative opacification in the periphery of the lung but patterns vary between aetiologies. ~~
  • Most common pattern on CXR is a reticular pattern. (nodular and mixed is also possible)
  • Poor correlation with disease severity / stage.
  • Chest X ray may appear normal in many cases.
  • Non-contract HRCT (with volumetric imaging) will reveal more details (even when CXR is normal)
  • Effusions: Rheumatoid effusions tend to be unilateral.

Enterococcus infection

In LVH, there is preferential flow to the sub-epicardium rather than the subendocardium so that there is reversal of the normal subendocardial to subepicardial flow at rest.

Rheumatoid arthritis

Synovium proliferates, grows onto articular surface of cartilage and becomes invaded by inflammatory cells. Cartilage becomes thinned due to inhibited nutrient diffusion and action of synovial cytokines.
Interaction of macrophages + T + B cells -> Over production of TNF-alpha -> recruitment of inflammatory cells + stimulation of osteoclasts -> synovitis and joint destruction.

  • development of antibodies against citrullinated antibodies - (ACPA)
  • smoking
    The typical presentation is gradual onset, chronic, symmetrical peripheral polyarthritis + systemic inflammation progressing over weeks to months. (But [[#Different forms of RA]] are recognized).

[!TIP] Mnemonic: The whole thing develops within a year
Source

>10 joints including at least one small joint -> gets 6 weightage points
>but 2 - 10 large joins : only 1 weightage point

  • Palindromic (AKA palindromic rheumatism) - monoarticular epidoes which last 24-48 hours, rare; About half 'resolve' to other types of RA.
  • Transient: lasts < 12 months; no permanent deformity.
  • Remitting: active for several years then remits; no permanent damage.
  • Rapidly progressive: Relentless progression over a few years leading to severe disability.
  • Monorarthritis of a large joint (knee, wrist, shoulder, hip) may be the only manifestation of RA.

Hands and wrists:

  • Fingers are affected early on; deformities include boutoniere and swan neck deformities.
  • PIP + MCP(DIP spared)

Feet

  • MTP (metatarsophalangeal) - common early manifestation
  • Hammer toe deformity
  • Flattening of the arhes

Shoulders -
Commonly affected; causes functional impairment, especially after rotator cuff tears (which occur in RA).

Elbows - can occur
Knees - also can occur.
Hips - less common than knees.

Cervical spine:
affects the synovial joint of the odontoid peg and the sinovitis and bone destruction at this point can cause atalandoaxial subluxation!

Non articular manifestations

  • Generalized aches and stiffness, weight loss, depression, fatigue
  • Bilateral Carpal tunnel syndrome
  • Rheumatoid lung disease: mnemonic: affects all parts of the lungs
    • Airways - bronchiectasis
    • Alveoli - infections (TB due to immunosuppressive drugs)
    • Interstitium - interstitial lung disease
    • Pleura - pleurisy
  • Neuropathy : peripheral symmetric sensory neuropathy or mononeuritis multiplex due to vasculitis of vasa vasorum.
  • Anaemia is universal: Normochromic, normocytic.
  • Thrombocytosis: with active disease

[!TIP] Mnemonic
RA affects the linings of the joints and linings of the organs (pleuritis, pericarditis) and linings of tendons (tenosynovitis)
